Spotify Wrapped for Your City¶

Context:¶

Imagine Spotify wants to release a city-specific version of their popular "Wrapped" feature. Your task is to analyze a dataset of song listening habits and create an interactive Streamlit dashboard that presents insightful visualizations about music preferences in a chosen city.

Dataset:¶

You can use the "Spotify Million Playlist Dataset" or a similar publicly available dataset containing information about songs, artists, playlists, and potentially user location data. https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/himanshuwagh/spotify-million

  • NOTE: Will use this playlist instead because it has location: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/dhruvildave/spotify-charts

Task Requirements:¶

  1. Data Analysis (40%):
  • Data Loading & Cleaning: Load the dataset, handle missing values, and perform any necessary data cleaning.
  • Data Transformation & Feature Engineering: Extract relevant features like song genre, release year, artist popularity, etc.
  • Create new features that could be insightful, e.g., "average tempo of songs listened to in the city."
  • Filter the data to focus on a specific city of your choice.
  • Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA): Conduct thorough EDA to understand the music listening trends in the chosen city.
  • Identify the top genres, artists, and songs popular in the city. Explore patterns based on time of day, day of the week, or seasonality.
  1. Data Visualization (30%):
  • Create at least 5 insightful visualizations using libraries like Matplotlib, Seaborn, or Plotly to showcase your findings from the EDA. Visualizations should effectively communicate:
  • The most popular genres in the city.
  • The top 10 most listened to artists and songs.
  • Any interesting trends observed based on time of day or day of the week.
  • Comparisons with global or national music trends (if data allows).
  • Focus on clarity and aesthetics:
  • Label your visualizations clearly and concisely.
  • Choose an appropriate color palette and visualization style for each plot.
  1. Streamlit Dashboard (30%):
  • Build an interactive Streamlit dashboard that presents your visualizations in an engaging and user-friendly way.
  • Incorporate interactive elements:
  • Allow users to select a specific genre or artist to filter the visualizations.
  • Implement a slider to adjust the time period for trend analysis.
  • Design for clarity and user experience:
  • Organize your dashboard logically with sections and headings.
  • Provide brief descriptions to guide users through the information presented.

Evaluation Criteria:¶

Correctness and depth of data analysis: How well did you clean, transform, and analyze the data to derive meaningful insights? Quality and effectiveness of visualizations: Are your visualizations informative, aesthetically pleasing, and easy to understand? Functionality and design of the Streamlit dashboard: Is your dashboard user-friendly, interactive, and visually appealing? Code quality and documentation: Is your code well-structured, commented, and easy to follow?

Bonus:¶

Implement machine learning to recommend songs or artists based on the city's preferences. Deploy your Streamlit app using platforms like Heroku or Streamlit Sharing.

Deliverables:¶

A Jupyter Notebook or Python script containing your data analysis and visualization code. A Streamlit application showcasing your interactive dashboard. A brief written report summarizing your findings and design choices.

Importing Essential liberaries¶

  • extract year and week
  • region and chart interaction (combine)
  • one hot encoding of region chart and trend EDA:
  • Summary statistics of rank and streams
  • Time series analysis number of songs or streams per month to observe trends
  • Region specific analysis compare top200 with top50
  • most popular songs by region
  • distribution of different trends to know how songs perform overtime
  • Artist popularity
  • Correlation Analysis rank and streams and time to identify potential relationships

shape_of_you_df = df[df['title'] == 'Shape of You']
shape_of_you_df = shape_of_you_df.sort_values('date')

# Create the line plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))  # Adjust figure size as needed
plt.plot(shape_of_you_df['date'], shape_of_you_df['rank'])
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Rank')
plt.title('Rank of "Shape of You" Over Time')

# Add markers to indicate rank increases and decreases
for i in range(1, len(shape_of_you_df)):
    if shape_of_you_df['rank'].iloc[i] > shape_of_you_df['rank'].iloc[i-1]:
        plt.plot(shape_of_you_df['date'].iloc[i], shape_of_you_df['rank'].iloc[i], marker='v', color='red')  # Downward triangle for rank decrease
    elif shape_of_you_df['rank'].iloc[i] < shape_of_you_df['rank'].iloc[i-1]:
        plt.plot(shape_of_you_df['date'].iloc[i], shape_of_you_df['rank'].iloc[i], marker='^', color='green')  # Upward triangle for rank increase

plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
Top 10 repeated songs and their occurances and ranking according to popularity¶
In [ ]:
top_10_songs = df['title'].value_counts().head(10).index
final_ranks = {}

# Get the final rank for each song
for song in top_10_songs:
    song_df = df[df['title'] == song]
    song_df = song_df.sort_values('date')
    final_ranks[song] = song_df['rank'].iloc[-1]  # Get the rank of the last (most recent) entry

# Create a bar chart with reversed y-axis
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.bar(final_ranks.keys(), final_ranks.values())
plt.xlabel('Song Name')
plt.ylabel('Final Rank (Lower is Better)')
plt.title('Final Ranks of Top 10 Repeated Songs')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()  # Invert the y-axis
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

streamlit_code = """
import streamlit as st
import pandas as pd
import altair as alt
import folium
from streamlit_folium import st_folium

# Load the entire dataset to get all countries
def load_full_data(filepath):
    return pd.read_csv(filepath)

# Load the entire dataset to get the full list of countries
full_data = load_full_data('df_withmonths.csv')

# Then, subset the data for other operations
def load_data(filepath, nrows=500):
    return pd.read_csv(filepath, nrows=nrows)

# Load the data (only 500 rows)
data = load_data('df_withmonths.csv')

# Optimize Data Types (Optional)
def optimize_data(df):
    df['month'] = df['month'].astype('category')
    df['trend'] = df['trend'].astype('category')
    df['artist'] = df['artist'].astype('category')
    df['region'] = df['region'].astype('category')  # Assuming 'region' represents the country
    return df

data = optimize_data(data)
full_data = optimize_data(full_data)

# Convert the unique values to a list
country_list = full_data["region"].unique().tolist()

# Streamlit Sidebar Filters
st.sidebar.header("Filters")

# Country filter
country = st.sidebar.selectbox("Select Country", options=sorted(country_list))  # Sorting for better usability

# Filter the data by the selected country
filtered_data = data[data["region"] == country]

# Convert the unique artist and trend values to a list
filtered_artist_list = filtered_data["artist"].unique().tolist()
filtered_trend_list = filtered_data["trend"].unique().tolist()

# Artist and Trend filters based on filtered country data
artist = st.sidebar.multiselect("Select Artist", options=sorted(filtered_artist_list), default=filtered_artist_list)
trend = st.sidebar.multiselect("Select Trend", options=filtered_trend_list, default=filtered_trend_list)

# Further filter the data by the selected artist and trend
filtered_data = filtered_data[(filtered_data["artist"].isin(artist)) & (filtered_data["trend"].isin(trend))]

# Display Data Table
st.write(f"## Spotify Top Tracks in {country}")
st.dataframe(filtered_data.head(100))  # Display only the first 100 rows

# Visualizations
# Bar Chart: Rank Distribution by Artist
st.write("## Rank Distribution by Artist")
rank_chart = alt.Chart(filtered_data).mark_bar().encode(
    x='artist:N',
    y='rank:Q',
    color='artist:N',
    tooltip=['title', 'rank', 'streams']
).interactive()
st.altair_chart(rank_chart, use_container_width=True)


# Pie Chart: Trend Proportion
st.write("## Trend Proportion")
trend_chart = alt.Chart(filtered_data).mark_arc().encode(
    theta=alt.Theta(field="streams", type="quantitative"),
    color=alt.Color(field="trend", type="nominal"),
    tooltip=['trend', 'streams']
).interactive()
st.altair_chart(trend_chart, use_container_width=True)

# Display Links to Spotify Tracks
st.write("## Spotify Links")
for i, row in filtered_data.iterrows():
    st.write(f"[{row['title']}]({row['url']}) by {row['artist']}")

"""

# Write the Streamlit code to a Python script
with open('spotify_dashboard.py', 'w') as f:
    f.write(streamlit_code)

print("Streamlit code saved to 'spotify_dashboard.py'")
